# AGENTS.md

## Purpose

Shared operating contract for platform work: clear routing, small safe changes, and evidence-based verification.

## Team values

- Tidy First
- CUPID (composable, Unix philosophy, predictable, idiomatic, domain-based)
- TDD
- lean delivery
- resilient systems
- secure by default
- observable by default
- maintainable by default
- small safe changes
- clarity over cleverness

## Core operating model

1. Clarify the request.
2. Route to the smallest suitable agent set.
3. Explore existing patterns before editing.
4. Keep structural cleanup separate from behavior changes when practical.
5. Use TDD for behavior changes.
6. Verify with real evidence before claiming success.
7. Use read-only review for risky, cross-domain, or production-facing work.

## Scope coverage

This team supports platform runtime, developer platform, services/CLIs/tooling, CI/CD, security, observability, architecture, and AI workflow improvement.

## Team roles

Use one implementation role by default. Add specialists only when they materially improve outcomes.

- `builder`: services, CLIs, automation, tooling
- `developer-platform-engineer`: Backstage, scaffolding, docs UX, templates
- `platform-engineer`: Kubernetes, GitOps, runtime, charts
- `orchestrator`: planning, routing, coordination
- `reviewer`: final read-only review
- `delivery-engineer`: GitHub, Actions, release workflows, CI/CD
- `security-engineer`: security-sensitive review
- `observability-engineer`: telemetry, Grafana, alerts, SLOs, runbooks
- `architect`: major design tradeoffs and capability shaping (use intentionally)
- `ai-workflow-engineer`: prompts, routing, commands, skills (use intentionally)

## Shared principles

- Prefer the smallest viable change.
- Do not mix unrelated refactors into task-focused work.
- Prefer declarative, GitOps-friendly changes.
- Prefer rollback-friendly changes and explicit risk notes.
- Never invent verification results.
- Never weaken security for convenience.
- Keep prompts short, focused, and task-specific.
- Keep default responses crisp: target <= 6 bullets unless the user asks for a deep dive.
- Add abstraction/config only when needed now; extract on second concrete use.
- Use skills for depth, not extra agents for every technology.
- In this repo, treat only repo-owned personal mise `00-*` fragments and managed helpers as in scope by default; do not modify unmanaged local `10-*`/`20-*` fragments unless explicitly asked.
- For mise task scripting, prefer bash for simple logic, Node.js for complex logic, and run Node via mise-managed latest Node wrappers.

## Routing defaults

- Start with one implementation role.
- Add specialty roles only when needed.
- Avoid overlapping experts on the same context.

## Ponytail usage policy

- Use Ponytail as a selective implementation discipline, not a global behavior override.
- Enabled by default for: `build`, `builder`, `developer-platform-engineer`, `delivery-engineer`.
- Optional `lite` usage for: `platform-engineer`, `observability-engineer`.
- Disabled for: reasoning/review/architecture roles (`orchestrator`, `reviewer`, `architect`, `security-engineer`, `ai-workflow-engineer`).
- Keep reliability guardrails intact: never skip validation, trust-boundary checks, security controls, accessibility, or rollback planning.
- If Ponytail and task requirements conflict, prioritize correctness, safety, and explicit acceptance criteria.

The full philosophy and principles are in `PONYTAIL.md.tmpl`.

## Verification rules

Default order unless repo conventions differ:
1. lint
2. tests
3. typecheck
4. build

For platform or infrastructure work, run the closest equivalent validation and include rollout or policy risk notes.

## Model routing policy

Use role-tier routing. Flagship reasoning roles use strongest reasoning routes, coding roles use strong coding routes, helper roles use fast cost-efficient routes.

OpenCode machine config is rendered from a single chezmoi template. Use profile-based rendering (`opencode.profile`) and avoid separate rendered profile files.
